body:
Refined the auto-generated functions that need `---@generic`. For example `deepcopy()`, which currently returns `any`.

There are other functions that could benefit from this but I couldn't prove that the changes worked. I think lua-language-server itself might have some bugs related to generic. For now, I only included the ones that I could verify are working as intended.

This PR edits:

- `:h copy()`
- `:h deepcopy()`
- `:h reduce()`
- `:h reverse()`
- `:h sort()`

<details>
<summary>Testing `copy()` / `deepcopy()`</summary>

```lua
---@class FooDeep
---@field bar string
---@field another integer

---@type FooDeep
local foo = {bar="asdf", another=123}
local copy = vim.fn.deepcopy(foo)
print(copy.another) -- NOTE: Is found, as expected
print(copy.does_not_exist) -- NOTE: Is missing, as expected

---@type FooDeep
local foo2 = {bar="asdf", another=123}
local copy2 = vim.fn.copy(foo2)
print(copy2.another) -- NOTE: Is found, as expected
print(copy2.does_not_exist) -- NOTE: Is missing, as expected
```
</details>

<details>
<summary>Testing `reduce()`</summary>

```lua
---@param accumulator string
---@param value string
local function reducer(accumulator, value)
  return (accumulator or "") .. value
end

local result = vim.fn.reduce({"a", "b", "c"}, reducer)
print(result:match("asdf")) -- NOTE: Works as expected
print(result:does_not_exist()) -- NOTE: Errors as expected
```
</details>

<details>
<summary>Testing `reverse()`</summary>

```lua
local data = {"a", "z", "b"}

local reversed = vim.fn.reverse(data)
print(reversed[1]:match("asdf")) -- NOTE: is found, as expected
reversed[1]:does_not_exist() -- NOTE: is missing, as expected
```
</details>

<details>
<summary>Testing `sort()`</summary>

```lua
---@class Foo2
---@field bar string
---@field another integer

---@type Foo2[]
local foo = {{bar="asdf", another=123}}
local copy = vim.fn.sort(foo)
print(copy[1].another)
print(copy[1].does_not_exist)
```
</details>

Unrelated to `@generic` but because I was in the neighborhood -

- `max` - currently returning any
- `min` - currently returning any
- `items` - currently accepts any argument (but really it needs a `table`)

As far as I know `min` `max` functions return a number, always. Currently they're typed to return any. If that's wrong and they actually can return non-numbers then I'll revert it.

## Question For Reviewers
`runtime/doc/builtin.txt` uses the raw parameter type / return type. Previously `any` and is now `T`. `T` is pretty commonly understood as just a name for "Type" but I wondered if you wanted to do some kind of replacement. Something like "For builtin.txt, when a generic is used in a function and that name is found in the param / return, replace it back from `T` to the type name" or something.

comment_data.body:
This looks wrong. The old format was a 3 string tuple of `name, type, desc`.

`[string, string, string?][]` might be a better type.
comment_data.diff_hunk:
@@ -17,9 +17,10 @@
 --- @field deprecated? true
 --- @field returns? string|false
 --- @field returns_desc? string
+--- @field generics string[] Used to write `---@generics` annotations over a function.
 --- @field signature? string
 --- @field desc? string
---- @field params [string, string, string][]
+--- @field params {[1]: string, [2]: string}[] The input of any `signature`.

comment_data.body:
This is perhaps another hint that suggests we need to migrate to using the meta files as the "source of truth" for the type info instead of re-inventing a type language in `eval.lua`.

Not a blocker for this PR, but just a note.

comment_data.body:
Keeping the source of truth as a pure structured format makes the generators much simpler overall and better accommodates all the other metadata eval functions have.

I wouldn't say we are re-inventing the type language, it is just being presented in a structured/unwound format.

comment_data.body:
The parser is far from perfect. It's just good enough to build documentation from it. And not requiring a parser is much simpler. It means people can add additional metadata without having to also update a parser.

Also note the descriptions here are maintained in vimdoc. If we move this to lua metafiles, this would ideally need to change to markdown, and thus the content of eval.txt will change significantly. Zeer didn't seem to like [converting tabs to spaces](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/26711) in that file. Converting to markdown seems like a harder sell.

comment_data.body:
I forgot to leave a note about this, thank you for reminding me - the original `[string, string, string][]` is incorrect.

This can be verified with `lua-language-server`

`lua-language-sever --check repro.lua`
`repro.lua`
```lua
---@class Foo
---@field [string, string string][]
```

`Diagnosis complete, 1 problems found, see ~/path/to/lua-language-server/libexec/log/check.json`

```json
{
    "file:///home/selecaoone/temp/annotation_key_test.lua": [
        {
            "code": "luadoc-miss-symbol",
            "data": "syntax",
            "message": "`]` expected.",
            "range": {
                "end": {
                    "character": 17,
                    "line": 1
                },
                "start": {
                    "character": 17,
                    "line": 1
                }
            },
            "severity": 2,
            "source": "Lua Syntax Check."
        }
    ]
}
```

`[string, string, string?][]` has the same problem.

Also if you run `:InspectTree`, the parsed tree contains ERROR on that line.

That said though my suggestion doesn't appear to work 100% either. I think it's a bug with LuaLS

```lua
---@class Foo
---@field [1] string

---@type Foo
local foo = {[1]="asdf"}

foo[2]:match("asdfasfd") -- This should error, but doesn't


---@class Bar
---@field thing string

---@type Bar
local foo = {thing="asdf"}

foo[2]:match("asdfasfd") -- This should error, but doesn't
foo.does_not_exist:match("asdfasfd") -- This should error, and it does
foo["does_not_exist"]:match("asdfasfd") -- This should error, but doesn't
```

It seems that accessing fields using the `["key_name"]` syntax does not check the type at all. So either my suggestion is wrong and there's a better way to define it or it's a bug with LuaLS. Not sure. But the previous syntax does cause an error

> Also if you run :InspectTree, the parsed tree contains ERROR on that line.

The output of InspectTree doesn't matter for Lua annotations. What matters is how LuaLS processes them.

> - the original [string, string, string][] is incorrect.

Your example is missing a comma.

Either way the original annotation was fine. The only correction is that the last field is optional.
